snippet.textDisplay: I’m an animal behaviorist. “Litter mate syndrome” has to do less with the cognitive function of a pair of dogs and more to do with how they are raised and conditioned. Without instilling my personal opinion on the importance of spaying and neutering all pets to help in combatting the amount of shelter dogs that are euthanized daily, to have these boys neutered would very literally reduce testosterone levels and male typical aggression. In addition, preventative measures could have easily been taken to separate the boys when not closely monitored until a professional could step in and assist with training. There are clearly so many options that were left unexplored, and as much as I’m happy Shadow did not end up in a shelter, I’m heartbroken for Maria and very disappointed in your lack of judgement and responsibility.

snippet.textDisplay: 3:03 We have a chihuahua mix that was a rescue. For the first few weeks we had her (we also had a very sweet yellow lab) she seemed fine. After about three weeks she became aggressive over food, and sometimes thinks she’s tougher than bigger dogs, which doesn’t work out for her. My aunt has a black lab (I think? Some kind of dog like that.) that’s usually very sweet, but one time we brought out chihuahua over, she growled, and my aunts dog wasn’t too happy. She went after her, it was so scary. We were all screaming and terrified. My dog was crying and yipping, trying to escape out from under the other dog. Our chihuahua was about 10 or 11 pounds then (again, she’s a mix) and this dog was probably 50 or 60. I thought we might need to take our dog to the hospital. In the end both dogs were completely fine, but it was probably the scariest thing that had ever happened to me.
